pullRequest.body:
Port of [mathlib#15763](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/15763)

We complete the construction of the Lie group of units of a complete normed ring.

To show that multiplication and inversion are smooth, we add some more lemmas:
1. For a manifold `M` whose chart structure is induced by an open embedding from `M` to `H`, the open embedding itself is a smooth manifold map.
2. The inverse of this open embedding is smooth on its range.
3. For a manifold map `f : M ‚Üí M'` whose target space `M'` has a chart structure induced by an open embedding `e' : M' ‚Üí H'`, if `e' ‚àò f` is smooth, then `f` is smooth.

Lemmas previously not ported are now ported:
1. `open_embedding.to_local_homeomorph_left_inv`
2. `open_embedding.to_local_homeomorph_right_inv`

---

nodes.body: I did some testing. Seems like the `_ _ _` can be avoided simply by naming the type class arguments `[CS : ChartedSpace H M]` and then doing `(CS := ‚Ä¶)` when calling the theorems.

> I did some testing. Seems like the `_ _ _` can be avoided simply by naming the type class arguments `[CS : ChartedSpace H M]` and then doing `(CS := ‚Ä¶)` when calling the theorems.

Nice! I like the new changes; looks much cleaner. I just re-reviewed everything and still think this is good to go.
Pushed one more commit. Now `ContMDiff.lean` and `SmoothManifoldWithCorners.lean` are both free of `@foo _ _ _`. Once CI goes through, we should be good to go.
@grunweg Thanks for splitting `ConMDiff.lean`. Do you think `Geometry.Manifold.ContMDiff.Atlas` is the right place for the lemmas `contMDiff_openEmbedding` etc.?

You're welcome. I now know much better what mathlib already has on these :-)

When I was splitting the file, I always thought about these lemma going into `ContMDiff/Basic.lean`. I think this fits slightly better than Atlas.lean, but I don't have a very strong preference.
In any case, can you augment the module docstring to mention these new results, please?

I let a few style comments again. Not blocking from my side. If you prefer (optional to me), you could certainly split
- the removal of Set qualifiers
- the changes to SmoothManifoldWithCorners
- using named arguments
each into a preliminary PR. (If I had reviewer rights, I'd approve these quickly. Even non-experts could approve those.)

~I split out #8776 for removing `Set.`, etc.,~ and #8780 to clean up variables in `SmoothManifoldWithCorners.lean`. Probably will keep `[CS : ChartedSpace]`, etc., in this PR.

May I say that I'm so impressed by your review, @grunweg. Every time, they improve the PR by a lot and even inspire further work.  üêô

Let's try a bit to simplify the `CS` arguments in your direction. If it doesn't quite work out, we can ask on Zulip or just revert back to `_ _ _`. If anything, we may gain some nice `LocalHomeomorph` lemmas. Thanks for looking into this.

I do slightly worry about dragging this PR on, since the original proofs were complete as of August 2022 in mathlib3.
I've fixed the first sorry, I'm still puzzled by the proofs breaking. Feel free to ask or revert these commits.

I've pushed a commit removing all CS annotations: there's a second proof breaking, just so you see what would be needed.
Feel free to revert these if dealing with these is too painful.

I've removed the remaining `CS` annotations. How to convince Lean to use the instances we want looks to be beyond my pay grade. I'd like the PR to go through sooner, and if people are sufficiently bothered by the `_ _ _ _`, we can open a new PR to fix those. Thanks for experimenting!

Pull request successfully merged into master.

Build succeeded:

  * [Lint style](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/7193381849/job/19591709032)

I took another close look: in light of #8702, I presume the named `ChartedSpace` arguments ought to be simplified. I tried doing so myself, but in every lemma, something breaks in the proof. I don't fully understand why this changes and how to fix it.

I pushed two commits; feel free to revert either or both:
- the frist is golfing a proof. (This means another tiny sorry pops up, which I'd consider missing API for local homeomorphisms or so.)
- the second removes the CS arguments from two lemmas: one lemma works out nicely (and can even be golfed accordingly); for the other, a proof breaks.

Thanks :tada:

bors merge

First of all: thank you for doing this! I also work on manifolds, I'm excited to see other people doing the same. And I'm excited for mathlib to gain more instances of manifolds. This is great.

I have a couple of style suggestions: these are all small. Most of them, I presume, relate to the transition to mathlib4. (I never worked with mathlib3, so that's just a guess.) Some are my personal taste. (In any case, I'm also relatively new to mathlib, so my taste for style is still developing. Feel free to disagree with what I say.)

I've read your files out of order - sorry if that makes things confusing.

Thanks for the changes; I really like where this is going. I took another look, find below some more comments: small things again.
- I think the application file is almost ready to go; I suspect one lemma can just be inlined.
- The @contMDiff stuff in ContMDiff is annoying; there ought to be a better way, but I don't see it.
- Some proofs on ContMDiff are a real tour de force. Thanks for sticking with this! I feel there should be a less painful way - but perhaps that just doesn't exist yet.

Except for these (which a more experienced reviewer should comment on), from my point of view this PR is ready to go!

- the frist is golfing a proof. (This means another tiny sorry pops up, which I'd consider missing API for local homeomorphisms or so.)
- the second removes the CS arguments from two lemmas: one lemma works out nicely (and can even be golfed accordingly); for the other, a proof breaks.

Thanks :tada:

As far as I can tell, the mathlib 3 PR was never merged (and probably won't). Do you still add #align statements in this case? I would guess not.
I never learned Lean 3 style; I know that mathlib4 style is different. If I understand correctly, this should be intended by two spaces (also elsewhere).

I like tweaking wording - any suggestion here does not imply yours is bad in any way! So, here's a suggestion - feel free to adapt or ignore: "For a complete normed ring `R`, the embeddings of the units `RÀ£` into `R` is a smooth map."
IIUC, this entire block should be indented by two spaces. (This is probably a style change in Lean 4.)
IIUC, mathlib4 style is to do `have : (val : RÀ£ ‚Üí R) ‚àò (fun x : RÀ£ => x‚Åª¬π) = Ring.inverse ‚àò val := by ext; simp` (i.e., use := by and not a subgoal).
You can golf this slightly using dot notation: `(contMDiff_val.comp contMDiff_fst).prod_mk_space (contMDiff_val.comp contMDiff_snd)`, similarly below.
If you want, you could golf this to `refine' fun x \mapsto ContMDiffAt.comp x _ (contMDiff_val x)` (and also use dot notation). I'm not 100% sure which style is better.
I presume the "None of this should be particularly difficult." is resolved now; can you update this?

Can you pull pull this into a section? Then, you can add a variables line containing e.g.
`{M : Type*} [TopologicalSpace M] [Nonempty M] {e : M ‚Üí H} (h : OpenEmbedding e) {n : WithTop ‚Ñï}`,
prettifying this even more :-)

I have the nagging feeling there should be a nicer way to write this than ~a dozen underscores (say, using Lean4's named arguments). I fail to find one, though. Perhaps a reviewer has a better idea --- or you already found the best way :shrug: .

This probably requires some changes in the `ContMDiff` API, so we probably shouldn't touch it in this PR. I suppose one could give names to the type class argument `[CS : ChartedSpace H M]` so Lean4's named argument works.
Here (and at a few more places in the proof) you have another opportunity to use dot notation, if you want :-)

  hf.of_comp_openEmbedding Units.openEmbedding_val

Inlining it is actually easy (replace `apply ContMDiff.of_comp_units_val` by `apply ContMDiff.of_comp_openEmbedding Units.openEmbedding_val` twice) and does not make the proof much longer.
The lemma has no new conceptual content; it is merely a specialisation of a known lemma.

I don't see this lemma being used anywhere else (hence, suggest inlining it). Am I overlooking something?

I'm not sure if there's a preference on `refine` vs `refine'`. Might make sense to ask on zulip (or wait for another reviewer to comment).
